item.yttr.glitchwep_explanation: [THIS STRING DOES NOT NEED TRANSLATED, IT IS A NOTE *FOR* TRANSLATORS] This syntax sucks, but the way the animation works needs to be aware of the different parts of the string. Square brackets delineate a group that is subject to animation, and they are prefixed with either a or b to specify which color they use. English assigns color A to the word Metastable, and the color B to the Rifle/Sword/etc word. For animating *part* of the string, such as grammatical gender suffixes, multiple groups with the same color can be specified. When the animation is playing, two groups at the same index that have not changed will not be animated. Every line must have the same number of groups. Text outside of groups will never be animated and uses the default color, which is useful for spaces or punctuation. Also, you can have as many or as few variants here as you like - the line count does not need to match English. The interpolation palette is a variety of characters with differing lengths, used to provide an effect sort of like the MAGIC format code but with more control.
